Introduction to Python Project : FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

FoodHub is a food aggregator company in Newyork city, that offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app. Customer places order on app and app takes care of informing restarents, assigning delivery partner to pick up and deliver the order, customer can rate the order in the app. FoodHub earns money by collecting a fixed margin on the delivery order from the restaurants.

Dataset¶

Dataset for analysis includes below columns order_id, customer_id, restarent_name, cuisine_type, cost_of_the_order,day_of_the_week, rating, food_preparation_time, delivery_time

Key Qustions to be answered¶

  • How many rows and columns are present in the data?
  • What are the datatypes of the different columns in the dataset?
  • Are there any missing values in the data? If yes, how will they be treated?
  • What insights can be drawn from statistical summaries of the data?
  • Which restaurants and cuisines are most popular?
  • How to identify top customers and frequent restaurant partners?
  • What are the notable trends in order costs and delivery times?

Objective¶

The objective is to get fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help the company enhance customer experience.

Data Dictionary¶

  1. order_id - Unique ID of the order
  2. customer_id - Unique ID of the customer
  3. restaurant_name - Name of the restaurant
  4. cuisine_type - Cuisine ordered by the customer
  5. cost_of_the_order - Cost of the order
  6. day_of_the_week - Weekday or Weekend
  7. rating - Rating given by customer out of 5
  8. food_preparation_time - Time taken by restaurants to prepare the food.
  9. delivery_time - Time taken by delivery person to deliver the food.

  • There are no outliers in order cost, indicating no customer has placed an order with much more higher cost.
  • The distribution is little bit right skewed, indicating most customers prefer to order within cost range of 11 to 15 dollers while maximum cost can go above 30 dollers.
  • There are three modes in the distribution, indicating there are multiple cost price that customers prefer while ordering food.

# Step 1: Calculate count of orders in each category
restarant_category_counts = df_complete['restaurant_name'].value_counts()

# Step 2: Define bins based on the counts - here's an example of using quantiles
restaurant_bin_edges = [1, 10, 50, 100, float('inf')]
restaurant_labels = ['Low', 'Medium', 'High', 'Very High']

restaurant_bins = pd.cut(restarant_category_counts, bins=restaurant_bin_edges, labels=restaurant_labels, right=False)

# Step 3: Create a new DataFrame to map original categories to the new bins
restaurant_category_groups = pd.DataFrame({'Category': restarant_category_counts.index, 'Counts': restarant_category_counts.values, 'restaurant_with_no_of_orders': restaurant_bins.values})

# Step 4: Merge this with your original data, if needed
restarant_data_df = df_complete.merge(restaurant_category_groups[['Category', 'restaurant_with_no_of_orders']], left_on='restaurant_name', right_on='Category', how='left').drop('Category', axis=1)

df_new = df_complete.copy()

# convert rating column to numeric column so that we can find average rating
df_new['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df_new['rating'], errors='coerce')

# function to find out if rating count is more than 50
def rating_count_more_than_fifty_new(group):
    # Calculate the number of ratings
    rating_count = group['rating'].count()
    return rating_count > 50

# highly_rated is a Series object reset_index function will convert it into dataframe
highly_rated_new = df_new.groupby(['restaurant_name']).apply(rating_count_more_than_fifty_new)

# highly_rated is a Series object reset_index function will convert it into dataframe
df_highly_rated_new = highly_rated_new.reset_index()
df_highly_rated_new.columns='restaurant_name','rating_count_more_than_fifty'

# merging df_highly_rated with df_cleaned to get complete picture
df_highly_rated_new = df_highly_rated_new.merge(df_new, on='restaurant_name')

# filter with rating_count_more_than_fifty = True
df_highly_rated_new = df_highly_rated_new[df_highly_rated_new['rating_count_more_than_fifty']]

# filter with mean of rating > 4
df_highly_rated_new.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].mean() > 4

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders.¶

In [ ]:
revenue = 0

# filter records where cost_of_the_order > 20
df_order_cost_greater_than_twenty = df_complete[df_complete['cost_of_the_order'] > 20]

# create new column fill it with 25% revenue
df_order_cost_greater_than_twenty['order_cost_greater_than_twenty_revenue'] = df_order_cost_greater_than_twenty.apply(lambda x : 0.25 * x['cost_of_the_order'], axis=1)

# get sum of all revenue
revenue = df_order_cost_greater_than_twenty['order_cost_greater_than_twenty_revenue'].sum()

# filter records where cost_of_the_order <= 20 and >5
df_order_cost_six_to_twenty = df_complete[(df_complete['cost_of_the_order'] > 5)&(df_complete['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20)]

# create new column fill it with 15% revenue
df_order_cost_six_to_twenty['order_cost_six_to_twenty'] = df_order_cost_six_to_twenty.apply(lambda x : 0.15 * x['cost_of_the_order'], axis=1)

# get sum of all revenue
revenue = revenue + df_order_cost_six_to_twenty['order_cost_six_to_twenty'].sum()

def calculate_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost < 5:
        return 0
    else:
        return cost *0.15

df_complete['revenue'] = df_complete['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)
